<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="tf1">
<sup><sup>*</sup></sup><p class="display-inline">Four women reported more than one race.</p>
</div></div></section><section id="s011"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Outcomes</h3>
<p>Comparisons of before and after decisional conflict scores indicated statistically significantly reductions in overall decisional conflict (Z = −7.225; <em>p</em> &lt; 0.001); and in all decisional conflict subscales including feeling uncertain (Z = −5.971; <em>p</em> &lt; 0.001), feeling unclear about values related to screening (Z = −6.457; <em>p</em> &lt; 0.001), and feeling uninformed and unsupported (Z = −7.067; <em>p</em> &lt; 0.001) (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>). However, reliability was lower than expected on two subscales (feeling uniformed, Cronbach-α = 0.621; feeling unsupported, Cronbach-α = 0.554). When these two subscales were combined based on a prior factor analysis,<sup><a href="#B30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B30">30</a></sup> the resulting Cronbach-αlevels were improved (total decisional conflict, Cronbach-α = 0.839; feeling uncertain, Cronbach-α = 0.884; feeling unclear about values, Cronbach-α = 0.728); and feeling uninformed and unsupported, Cronbach-α = 0.720).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T2"><h4 class="obj_head">
<span class="font-variant-small-caps">Table</span> 2.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p><span class="font-variant-small-caps">Changes Between Initial and Subsequent Scores on the Decisional Conflict Scale and Subscales</span></p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="hsides" rules="groups">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" span="1">
<col align="left" span="1">
<col align="left" span="1">
<col align="left" span="1">
<col align="left" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1"> </th>
<th align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><em>Before mean (SD)</em></th>
<th align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><em>After mean (SD)</em></th>
<th align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">
<em>Change</em><sup><a href="#tf2" class="usa-link">*</a></sup>
</th>
<th align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">
<em>Significance</em><sup><a href="#tf2" class="usa-link">*</a></sup>
</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Total decision conflict</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">46.33 (27.04)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">8.33 (15.58)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Z = −7.225</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">
<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Uncertainty subscale</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">55.00 (41.71)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">15.00 (31.57)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Z = −5.971</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">
<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Unclear values subscale</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">51.33 (37.19)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">6.00 (18.30)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Z = −6.457</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">
<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Combined uninformed and unsupported subscales</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">43.44 (26.75)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">6.89 (12.88)</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">Z = −7.067</td>
<td align="center" colspan="1" rowspan="1">
<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="tf2">
<sup><sup>*</sup></sup><p class="display-inline">Wilcoxon ranked-sum test results.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="tf3"><p>SD, standard deviation.</p></div>
</div></section><p>Women also reported improved decision self-efficacy after using the Mammopad decision aid (79.67 vs. 95.73; Z = 6.816, p &lt; 0.001). The Decision Self-Efficacy Scale demonstrated acceptable internal reliability (Cronbach-α = 0.857). Women with the lowest initial decision self-efficacy scores demonstrated the largest increases (<a href="#f3" class="usa-link">Fig. 3</a>). Most women reported that they intended to have a mammogram before age 50, both before and after using Mammopad, and there was no significant change over time (Z = 1.543, <em>p</em> = 0.123).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f3"><h4 class="obj_head"><strong>FIG. 3.</strong></h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=4683542_fig-3.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/0cb7/4683542/2b8cb3cfec75/fig-3.jpg" loading="lazy" height="412" width="700" alt="FIG. 3."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Decision self-efficacy difference scores. The bee swarm diagram plots the distribution of women's difference scores (before–after) as a function of their before scores. Each initial score group is represented by a different color in the diagram; groups of women with the same initial and difference scores are arranged in a horizontal array centered over the corresponding initial score value on the <em>x</em>-axis. Color images available online at <a href="http://www.liebertpub.com/jwh" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">www.liebertpub.com/jwh</a></p></figcaption></figure><p>Women rated how much information they learned from the Mammopad decision aid on a scale from 1 (lowest) to 10 (highest), with a median response of 7 (interquartile range of 3). The Preparation for Decision Making Scale, which ranges from 0 to 100, indicated that the women felt the decision aid prepared them to make a shared decision with clinical providers (mean 73.2, standard deviation 18.1). This scale was highly reliable in our sample (Chronbach-α = 0.904).</p></section></section><section id="s012"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>This is the first study to develop and evaluate a mammography screening decision aid that includes a validated personal risk assessment instrument to help average-risk women in their forties decide whether to screen for breast cancer. While women with above-average risk status were ineligible to use the decision aid part of Mammopad in the study, they were able to identify their risk factors and consider personalized screening alternatives with their health care providers. The dual purposes of risk assessment and decision aid have proven useful to the clinical practices participating in the study to efficiently identify women who may particularly benefit from screening. The participating clinics asked to be notified of women at increased risk so they could follow-up with appropriate screening, and are now working toward implementing Mammopad as a standard practice for all age-appropriate women.</p>
<p>Most patients want to be informed and involved in decisions about their medical care.<sup><a href="#B31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B31">31</a></sup> The decision aid was intentionally designed to educate and to support evidence-based shared decision making about mammography screening between a woman and her primary care clinician. The results indicated that women learned new information about breast cancer screening and felt less conflicted about their screening decisions after using the decision aid. Women reported more confidence in their abilities to enter shared decision making as measured by decision self-efficacy. This was particularly true of women who reported low confidence in ability to prepare for this decision, suggesting that decision aids are particularly needed for women who are the least informed and least confident to discuss their screening options.</p>
<p>Implementing the Mammopad decision aid as a mobile application on an iPad mini was important for providing a user-friendly experience for both patients and study coordinators. Patients could easily hold the lightweight tablets in their laps and the touch screens were easier to use than a mouse. Despite the small tablet size, the screens were still large enough for easy reading and interaction. The size of the iPad mini made them easy for study coordinators to store and transport securely while the battery life allowed them to be used throughout a clinic day. We presume we would achieve similar benefits using other small touch screen mobile devices, but probably not with smartphones since the reduced screen size would make text and graphics harder to read.</p>
<p>A limitation of this study is that shared decision making was measured only through the patient's perspective. Few studies have provided direct evidence of the effectiveness of screening decision aids on the actual decision making discussion between patients and providers.<sup><a href="#B32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B32">32</a></sup> In addition, this study included a small sample of English-speaking women, most with higher than high school education, in a single rural geographical area and should be replicated in other populations. For this region of Oregon, we recruited fewer women with only high school education and also fewer Latinas, than expected. In the future, we plan to develop a Spanish version of Mammopad. We did not record the education level of the women who declined but did note the most common reasons for declining: conflict with work and lack of transportation or childcare. Future studies would need to address these barriers in order to obtain a more representative sample. While the current study provides some evidence of improved decision making with Mammoad, future studies should also compare the use of Mammopad to other types of decision making tools in a randomized trial.</p>
<p>Some participating clinics scanned the women's reports from Mammopad and attached them to the medical record requiring staff time. Future studies could provide a more seamless workflow, such as providing the decision aid via a patient portal prior to an upcoming visit.<sup><a href="#B33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B33">33</a></sup> This approach would prepare patients and providers to discuss screening options, concerns, and values and form a shared plan when they next meet.</p>
<p>The strengths of this study include the use of a mobile application that provides access to many users, as demonstrated among the rural women enrolled in the study. The risk assessment instrument and decision aid information were based on current evidence of effectiveness,<sup><a href="#B2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B2">2</a>,<a href="#B3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B3">3</a>,<a href="#B7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B7">7</a>,<a href="#B18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B18">18–20</a></sup> and are consistent with current recommendations of the United States Preventive Services Task Force for mammography screening<sup><a href="#B1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B1">1</a></sup> and assessment for breast cancer risk.<sup><a href="#B34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="B34">34</a></sup> The development of Mammopad was extensive and rigorous and involved users and experts at several points. The study used established and validated scales to determine outcomes. Further work is needed to evaluate the effectiveness of Mammopad on provider and patient communication, decision making, and clinical outcomes in a prospective randomized controlled trial.</p></section><section id="s013"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusions</h2>
<p>We designed and evaluated an electronic mobile application that included an individualized breast cancer risk assessment instrument and a decision aid to guide decisions about mammography screening for average-risk women in their forties. Women reported less conflict about their decisions for mammography screening and felt more confident to make decisions after using the decision aid. The decision aid was particularly effective for women who lacked self-efficacy to make screening decisions.</p></section><section id="sec14"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
